================================================================================
LICENSE — placeholder (team has not yet picked one)
================================================================================

Until the team explicitly selects and replaces this file with a real license,
the contents of this repository are:

  Copyright (c) 2026 Stock-Back-Test-System contributors. All rights reserved.

No license is granted to copy, modify, distribute, sublicense, or use this
software outside the team that has been granted access. Contributors retain
their own copyright on their contributions, licensed to the team for use
within this repository.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

When the team is ready to commit to a license, replace this entire file with
the canonical text for the chosen license. Common reasonable choices for a
small team that may eventually open up the project:

  - MIT — minimal, permissive, easy to read; everyone can do almost anything
    as long as the copyright notice ships with the software. Best for tools
    you want others to use and embed.

  - Apache-2.0 — permissive like MIT, with an explicit patent grant and
    contributor terms; better protection for projects that may attract
    commercial use or contributions from companies.

  - BSD-3-Clause — permissive, classic; very similar to MIT.

  - MPL-2.0 — file-level copyleft; modifications to MPL files must be shared,
    but linking from non-MPL code is fine. Useful if you want to keep core
    files open while allowing closed-source extensions.

  - GPL-3.0 — strong copyleft; any distributor of binaries must share the
    source. Good if you want every downstream user to also be a contributor;
    avoid if you have any plan to ship closed-source plugins or commercial
    extensions.

  - Proprietary / "All rights reserved" (this current file) — keep as-is
    until decided.

If you eventually decide to dual-license (e.g. AGPL + commercial), record
that in an ADR and update this file accordingly.

For the current dependency-license rules (what the project itself can
*depend on*, regardless of how the project is licensed), see
Docs/Decisions/dependencies.md and Docs/Governance/AGENTS.md §6.
